4. Data Collection: Present tables of ΩSpin_q(pt) and H_p(BG₂;ℤ) (context: authoritative_data_on_spin_bordism_classes_integral_homology_bg2_and_ahss_setup_for_ospin_asterisk).
5. Spectral Sequence Analysis: Summarize E₂-page table (context: classify_total_degree_12_bordism_via_ahss_for_BG2), differential analysis, Eₒ-page, extension resolution, leading to ΩSpin₁₂(BG₂)≅ℤ⁸.
6. Reduction to \(\widetilde\Omega\): Explain the quotient by the image of ΩSpin₁₂(pt) and derive \(\widetilde\Omega^{\rm Spin}_{12}(BG_2)\cong\mathbb Z^5\) (context: compute_12d_spin_bordism_of_BG2_with_reduction).
7. Discussion: Interpretation of summands, geometric meaning (homology origins in degrees 4,8,12), and potential applications.

Format with clear section headings, numbered equations where needed, and tables. Include the final result in a highlighted box in the Results or Conclusion section.' | Agent (Report Writer): '# Computation of the Reduced 12-Dimensional Spin Bordism of \(BG_2\)

---

## Abstract

We compute the reduced 12-dimensional Spin bordism group of the classifying space \(BG_2\), finding an isomorphism 
\[
\widetilde{\Omega}^{\mathrm{Spin}}_{12}(BG_2) \cong \mathbb{Z}^5.
\]
This calculation uses the Atiyah–Hirzebruch spectral sequence (AHSS) with integral homology of \(BG_2\) and classical Spin bordism of a point, analyzing differentials and extensions to fully determine the group structure.

---

## 1. Introduction

The Spin bordism groups \(\Omega_{*}^{\mathrm{Spin}}(X)\) of a space \(X\) encode bordism classes of closed Spin manifolds equipped with maps into \(X\). Understanding these groups provides deep insights in geometry and topology, particularly in questions of manifold classification, index theory, and string-theoretic applications.

For the exceptional Lie group \(G_2\), and specifically its classifying space \(BG_2\), computing the Spin bordism groups informs on characteristic classes associated to \(G_2\)-structures. The *reduced* Spin bordism \(\widetilde{\Omega}_{*}^{\mathrm{Spin}}(BG_2)\) is defined as the cokernel of the map induced by the basepoint inclusion:
\[
\widetilde{\Omega}_{*}^{\mathrm{Spin}}(BG_2) := \Omega_{*}^{\mathrm{Spin}}(BG_2) \Big/ \mathrm{Im}\big(\Omega_{*}^{\mathrm{Spin}}(\mathrm{pt}) \to \Omega_{*}^{\mathrm{Spin}}(BG_2)\big).
\]
This isolates bordism classes reflecting genuine topological data of \(BG_2\) beyond the trivial classifying space.

This report presents a detailed computation of \(\widetilde{\Omega}_{12}^{\mathrm{Spin}}(BG_2)\).

---

## 2. Background

### 2.1 Spin Bordism Groups

For a point, the Spin bordism groups \(\Omega_q^{\mathrm{Spin}}(\mathrm{pt})\) are classical and extensively studied. They are known to contain free and torsion parts, with well-understood generators up to degree 12 (see Stong [1968]).

### 2.2 The Group \(G_2\) and \(BG_2\)

The group \(G_2\) is a simply connected, compact, exceptional Lie group of dimension 14. Its classifying space \(BG_2\) encapsulates \(G_2\)-principal bundles, and its integral homology is known to be torsion-free and concentrated in certain degrees, with explicit computations by Borel (1953) and Mimura–Toda (1991).

### 2.3 Atiyah–Hirzebruch Spectral Sequence (AHSS)

The AHSS computes generalized homology theories via a spectral sequence with
\[
E_2^{p,q} = H_p(BG_2; \Omega_q^{\mathrm{Spin}}(\mathrm{pt})) \implies \Omega^{\mathrm{Spin}}_{p+q}(BG_2).
\]
Differentials and extension problems must be analyzed to deduce the final bordism groups.

---

## 3. Data Collection

### 3.1 Spin Bordism Groups \(\Omega_q^{\mathrm{Spin}}(\mathrm{pt})\) for \(0 \leq q \leq 12\)

| \(q\) | \(\Omega^{\mathrm{Spin}}_q(\mathrm{pt})\) | Comments / Generators             |
|:-----:|:-----------------------------------------:|----------------------------------|
| 0     | \(\mathbb{Z}\)                            | Point class                      |
| 1     | \(\mathbb{Z}/2\)                          | Arf invariant torsion            |
| 2     | \(\mathbb{Z}/2\)                          |                                |
| 3     | 0                                         |                                |
| 4     | \(\mathbb{Z}\)                            | Signature index                 |
| 5     | 0                                         |                                |
| 6     | 0                                         |                                |
| 7     | 0                                         |                                |
| 8     | \(\mathbb{Z}^2\)                          | KO-index, higher genera         |
| 9     | \(\mathbb{Z}/2\)                          |                                |
| 10    | \(\mathbb{Z}/2\)                          |                                |
| 11    | 0                                         |                                |
| 12    | \(\mathbb{Z}^3\)                          | Including KO invariants          |

*Source: Stong (1968)*

---

### 3.2 Integral Homology \(H_p(BG_2; \mathbb{Z})\) for \(0 \leq p \leq 12\)

| \(p\) | \(H_p(BG_2; \mathbb{Z})\)          | Comments                               |
|:-----:|:----------------------------------:|--------------------------------------|
| 0     | \(\mathbb{Z}\)                     | Connected                           |
| 1     | 0                                 | \(G_2\) simply connected           |
| 2     | 0                                 |                                      |
| 3     | 0                                 |                                      |
| 4     | \(\mathbb{Z}\)                    | Generated by characteristic classes |
| 5     | 0                                 |                                      |
| 6     | \(\mathbb{Z}\)                    | Torsion-free                         |
| 7     | 0                                 |                                      |
| 8     | \(\mathbb{Z}\)                    | Higher characteristic classes       |
| 9     | 0                                 |                                      |
| 10    | 0                                 |                                      |
| 11    | 0                                 |                                      |
| 12    | \(\mathbb{Z}^2\)                  | Two generators                      |

*Sources: Borel (1953), Mimura–Toda (1991)*

---

## 4. Spectral Sequence Analysis for Total Degree 12

Total degree constraint:
\[
p + q = 12, \quad E_2^{p,q} = H_p(BG_2; \Omega_q^{\mathrm{Spin}}(\mathrm{pt})).
\]

### 4.1 Computation of Nonzero Terms \(\mathbf{E_2^{p,q}}\) at \(p+q=12\)

| \(p\) | \(q\) | \(H_p(BG_2; \mathbb{Z})\) | \(\Omega_q^{\mathrm{Spin}}(\mathrm{pt})\) | \(E_2^{p,q}\)                          |
|:-----:|:-----:|:---------------------------:|:------------------------------------------:|:-------------------------------------:|
| 0     | 12    | \(\mathbb{Z}\)              | \(\mathbb{Z}^3\)                          | \(\mathbb{Z}^3\)                      |
| 4     | 8     | \(\mathbb{Z}\)              | \(\mathbb{Z}^2\)                          | \(\mathbb{Z}^2\)                      |
| 8     | 4     | \(\mathbb{Z}\)              | \(\mathbb{Z}\)                            | \(\mathbb{Z}\)                        |
| 12    | 0     | \(\mathbb{Z}^2\)            | \(\mathbb{Z}\)                            | \(\mathbb{Z}^2\)                      |
| Others|       | 0 or torsion                | 0 or torsion                             | 0                                    |

All other \((p,q)\) pairs with \(p+q = 12\) vanish since either homology or bordism group is zero or torsion annihilates tensor.

---

### 4.2 Differential Analysis

- Differentails in AHSS:
\[
d_r: E_r^{p,q} \to E_r^{p-r, q + r -1}.
\]

- For \(E_r^{p,q}\) with \(p+q=12\), targets have total degree \(11\).
- Checking homology \(H_{p-r}(BG_2)\) and \(\Omega_{q+r-1}^{\mathrm{Spin}}(\mathrm{pt})\) for targets reveals all such groups vanish.
- Negative homology degrees and zeros in source or target groups exclude nontrivial differentials.
- Hence, **all differentials involving total degree 12 terms vanish**.

---

### 4.3 \(E_\infty\) Page and Extensions

With no differentials, 
\[
E_\infty^{p,q} = E_2^{p,q}.
\]

Since groups involved are all free abelian, no nontrivial extensions appear. The total graded group for degree 12 is the direct sum:
\[
\Omega_{12}^{\mathrm{Spin}}(BG_2) \cong \mathbb{Z}^3 \oplus \mathbb{Z}^2 \oplus \mathbb{Z} \oplus \mathbb{Z}^2 = \mathbb{Z}^8.
\]

---

## 5. Reduction to \(\widetilde{\Omega}\)

The forgetful map from Spin bordism of a point injects the \(\mathbb{Z}^3\) summand \(E_\infty^{0,12}\) into \(\Omega^{\mathrm{Spin}}_{12}(BG_2)\). The reduced Spin bordism group is the quotient by this image:
\[
\widetilde{\Omega}^{\mathrm{Spin}}_{12}(BG_2) := \Omega^{\mathrm{Spin}}_{12}(BG_2)/\mathrm{Im}\big(\Omega^{\mathrm{Spin}}_{12}(\mathrm{pt})\big).
\]

Therefore,
\[
\widetilde{\Omega}^{\mathrm{Spin}}_{12}(BG_2) \cong \mathbb{Z}^8 / \mathbb{Z}^3 \cong \mathbb{Z}^5,
\]
with the summands given explicitly by:
\[
\widetilde{\Omega}^{\mathrm{Spin}}_{12}(BG_2) \cong \mathbb{Z}^2 \oplus \mathbb{Z} \oplus \mathbb{Z}^2,
\]
originating from:
- \(E_\infty^{4,8} = H_4(BG_2; \Omega_8^{\mathrm{Spin}}(\mathrm{pt})) \cong \mathbb{Z}^2\),
- \(E_\infty^{8,4} = H_8(BG_2; \Omega_4^{\mathrm{Spin}}(\mathrm{pt})) \cong \mathbb{Z}\),
- \(E_\infty^{12,0} = H_{12}(BG_2; \Omega_0^{\mathrm{Spin}}(\mathrm{pt})) \cong \mathbb{Z}^2\).

---

## 6. Discussion

The five summands reflect distinct geometric features of Spin manifolds with \(G_2\)-structure classified by \(BG_2\). The degrees \(4, 8, 12\) correspond to homology generators of \(BG_2\) tied to characteristic classes:

- Degree 4, connected to first Pontrjagin-like classes,
- Degrees 8 and 12 relate to higher characteristic classes and products thereof.

No torsion appears, indicating a free abelian group structure and simplifying potential applications, for example in detecting topological invariants of \(G_2\)-manifolds or in string-theoretic compactifications where \(G_2\) holonomy is prevalent.

---

## 7. Conclusion

\[
\boxed{
\widetilde{\Omega}^{\mathrm{Spin}}_{12}(BG_2) \cong \mathbb{Z}^5.
}
\]

This group is freely generated by bordism classes arising from nontrivial homology in degrees 4, 8, and 12 paired with Spin bordism classes in degrees 8, 4, and 0, respectively. No torsion factors or differential extensions affect this structure.

---

## 8. References

- R. E. Stong, *Notes on Cobordism Theory*, University of Chicago, 1968. [Online](https://www.maths.ed.ac.uk/~v1ranick/papers/stongcob.pdf)
- A. Borel, *Sur la cohomologie des espaces fibrés principaux et des espaces homogènes de groupes de Lie compacts*, Ann. of Math. (2) 57 (1953), 115–207.
- Y. Mimura and H. Toda, *Topology of Lie Groups I and II*, Translations AMS 91, 1991.
- A. Hatcher, *Spectral Sequences* notes, available at author's webpage.
- J. F. Adams, *Infinite Loop Spaces*, Annals of Mathematics Studies 90, Princeton Univ. Press, 1995.

---

*End of Report*'
